35    /**
36    * Computes "may be" reaching use for all definitions of each variables.
37    *
38    * A use of {@code A} in {@code alert(A)} is a "may be" reaching use of
39    * the definition of {@code A} at {@code A = foo()} if at least one path from
40    * the use node reaches that definition and it is the last definition before
41    * the use on that path.
42    *
43    */

62    /**
63    * May use definition lattice representation. It captures a product
64    * lattice for each local (non-escaped) variable. The sub-lattice is
65    * a n + 2 power set element lattice with all the Nodes in the program,
66    * TOP and BOTTOM. This is better explained with an example:
67    *
68    * Consider: A sub-lattice element representing the variable A represented
69    * by { N_4, N_5} where N_x is a Node in the program. This implies at
70    * that particular point in the program the content of A is "upward exposed"
71    * at point N_4 and N_5.
72    *
73    * Example:
74    *
75    * A = 1;
76    * ...
77    * N_3:
78    * N_4: print(A);
79    * N_5: y = A;
80    * N_6: A = 1;
81    * N_7: print(A);
82    *
83    * At N_3, reads of A in {N_4, N_5} are said to be upward exposed.
84    */
